ol system as a whole in Hampshire. The report sets out the background </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the academies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> features of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> size and diversity in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Hampshire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which make a comparison between academy performance and the performance of maintained schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">especially valid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The conclusions of the report are supported by data from Hampshire schools, although with the academies programme only in its third academic ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar, such conclusions are set against the caveat of limited trend data.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The overwhelming conclusion is that school status remains at best an unreliable determinant of school performance.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">current position </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in Hampshire</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire has seventy seco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools of which sixty-three are 11-16 and seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">       </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11-18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Hampshire operates a highly successful tertiary system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Of those seventy schools, twenty three have converted to academy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> status (33%) seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a sponsor (10%) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">forty (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">57</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">%) are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ained schools. The status of schools does not divide along performance lines with two of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> four </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">top performing schools in Hampshire currently operating as converter academies and two as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintained schools. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lowest performing schools are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> one is a sponsored academy and one a converter academy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire is, perhaps, unusual in that it has not adopted an ideological stance to academy con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">version but has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> responded to individual schools bas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed upon evidence of performance and likely impact. This “neutral” approach has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> grown out of the exp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Grant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Maintained (GM) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">status which resulted in seven schools becoming very isolated both from the LA and from other secondary schools.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provided experience of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">risks to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools which gain “freedom” without the leadership capacity to make best use of it. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire’s current “active neutrality” on the question of school status is also borne out of a strong political commitment to ret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ain and fund the role and identity of the County Council as a local education authority. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Hampshire school system is characterised by an inclusive consultative structure, good relationships between most schools and between most schools and the LA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ch is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> based upon sound knowledge and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the expectation of challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and a thriving Children’s Trust with shared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commitment to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> some key aims. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> crafted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> role for the LA in Hampshire in driving the shared agenda, for example, the poor performance of less advantaged children in the county. This has been a priority since the Children and Young People’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lan in 2007/8 and it has driven investment and much joi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt working. It is true that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improvement has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">made;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ree </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chool </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> gap remains stubbornly wide in Hampshire,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wider in converter academies than in maintained schools or sponsored academies. The LA has visited all schools of all statuses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and there is a collective will to tackle this. All schools belon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g to the consultative structure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Hampshire Heads have reformed as “Hampshire Secondary Education Leaders,” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order to signal that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inclusivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regardless of school status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no wis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h to return to the days of GM conflict. To that end the LA is, and has remained, neutral about school status,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> based mainly upon local evidence that school status has far less impact upon school performance than school leadership. The LA has, therefore, ens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that, where schools want to convert and their performance is not a cause for concern, that conversion is as rapid and as trouble-free as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here schools are failing, a sponsored solution is actively considered and, when this is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the correct solution, sponsors sought and the solution expedited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The significant difference in Hampshire, however, is that the local authority school improvement service is extensive, robust and credible. It is the service of choice for most secondary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools, regardless of status, and it has twenty years of experience of selling high quality school improvement service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to schools. In addition, the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ounty Council considers the quality of education which Hampshire children receive to be a statutory respo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsibility of which it can not and would not divest itself. The County Council has, therefore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continued to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> invest in a core school improvement service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all maintained schools and to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all schools. This means that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintained schools receiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a full service and those which have converted have a full service which the majority purchase. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is, therefore, possible to compare the fate of academies and of maintained schools in Hampshire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, since</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all schools have a similar offer. Hampshire County Council endeavours to be “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">status-blind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">” in its dealings with all schools except insofar as the charging for activity where schools now have the funding themselves.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Statutory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">responsibilities and interven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities remain responsible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, under the 2006 Education Act,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of education children receive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in their administrative area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, despite subsequent legislation introducing greater school autonomy and encouraging sponsorship. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LAs also have substantial powers of intervention which successive legislation has attempted to compel them to use effectively. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The withdrawal from this function by some LAs has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in our view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not only been ill advised, with some catastrophic consequences, but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is not supported by legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire County Council takes this responsibility se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">riously. The Council refunded the top-slice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">removed mid-year from Children’s Services budgets in 2010 in order to fund notional future academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a Leadership and Learning Partner (LLP) for every</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintained school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the termination </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nationally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> School Improvement Programme (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SIP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The LLP is a fundamental aspect of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintaining a heal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thy school system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Hampshire’s converter academies also buy into this service. The allocation of LLP time depends on the needs of the school, with those causing concern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> allocated more time than outst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anding schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but all schools have a partner who is either an LA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inspector/adviser or a Hampshire headteacher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The political support which school improvement receives from all parties within the County Council makes it possible for the challenge and support function to be robust without being politically motivated.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have ceased to maintain close and regular contact with all schools have struggled to maintain “intelligence,” about school performance beyond data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Such data only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shows decline after it has already happened. Effective school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> work requires the brokerage of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> early,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> tailor-made and effective school to school support. Without intimate knowledge of good and outstanding schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such brokerage is impossible and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence sugge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sts, it is insufficiently focussed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and less likely to bring about sustained improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintains a district management structure which challenges schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and ensures support is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> co-ordinated and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accountable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire maintains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an extensive and highly regarded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sold service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, set up in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the early 1990s. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">popular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provides </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bespoke training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, development, advice, curriculum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">materials and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inspection for all subject areas, including those not within the taught </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">curriculum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and for leadership, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including governance. Almost all Hampshire schools buy this service which is sold at the same rate for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintained schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsive service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is also deployed at LA central cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, to any Hampshire school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when need is acute. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other LAs and out of county schools also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">purchase the Hampshire S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chool </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mprovement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ervice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (HIAS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is this sold activity which allows Hampshire to retain a professional, highly trained and experienced team of inspectors and advisers lead by centrally fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nded sen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ior officers, so that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exercise its challenge, support and intervention function in accordance with legislation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> All schools, academies and maintained schools, benefit from this service because Hampshire children attend all of them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> same approach informs the LA’s attitude to underperformance and the right to challenge all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, regardless of status,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on behalf of Hampshire children. The use of intervention powers is robust, and the LA has i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nstituted some additional “powers,”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s a review of school leadership at every level, for which it has negotiated the agreement of Hampshire headteacher and teacher unions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This relates to our evidenced conviction that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of leadership is a far more important factor than school status.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of Hampshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">schools – the evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire provides an unusual opportunity to make comparisons between the performance of different types of school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which serve a varied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">population of advantage, disadvantage, rural, costal and urban communities – very much </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">representative of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the nation as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with some 2% of the nation’s schools and children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This report will consider two external</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mechanisms for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">judging school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> performa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nce; the results achieved in public examinations and Ofsted judgements of school effectiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the headline figure of 5+A*-C GCSE grades, including English and mathematics, all types of schools in Hampshire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with the exception of the sponsored academi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es, experienced a decline in results between 2011 and 2012, largely as a result of the recalibration of the English pass grade. Maintained schools declined by three percentage points, converter academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, from a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comparatively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> high base at the point of conversion,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by two percentage points and sponsored academies improved from a very low base, by three percentage points.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clearly schools needed to respond to the increased demands of a higher grade boundary and the evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suggests that maintained schools and sponsored academies have done that. Results between 2012 and 2013 improved in maintained schools by two percentage points and in sponsored academies by nearly six percentage points. However, in converter acade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mies GCSE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">results declined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">still further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a half</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a percentage point between 2012 and 2013. This is summarised in the table below.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This data has its limitations since it covers only three academic years and the sample is small which means that the variations have l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imited statistical significance. The data does show, however, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at sponso