span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 1.3pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a recent response to the Secretary of State, the Leader of Hampshire County Council quoted two specific examples. The Clere School, placed into Special Measures in December 2011 remained an LA maintained school with an IEB chaired by a senior officer. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his school was judged by Ofsted to be “Good” on all measures after five terms and removed from Special Measures straight to “Good” in July 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 1.3pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 1.3pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bridgemary, on the other hand, became a sponsored academy wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th the support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the Local Authority in 2012 sinc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, whist judged as Requiring Improvement and marginally above government floor standards, its progress had been slow and the LA judged, wrongly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a sponsored solution would be in the school’s interests. In 2013 its results declined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to below</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> floor at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 34</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.6 %and the Ofsted inspection in May 2013 judged the school to have serious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">weaknesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Neither of these examples are definitive but they endorse the view of Hampshire County Council, that the intervention needed in schools which are failing or at risk of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> doing so must be tailored to individual circumstances. Sponsorship is a tool which can bring about rapid improvement but it is not the only tool which L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As have and they must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> select the intervention most likely to bring about results.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Taken as a whole, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the above data shows little difference in the overall performance of different types of schools in Hampshire. Thos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schools which converted did so from a higher general base than tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se which received sponsors. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he maintained schools in Hampshire cover the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">entire range for prior attainment. Individual schools of all types have shown improvement and decline, in some the FSM gap has reduced to nothing and in others it has remained wide or even increased. Whilst maintained schools show a substantially better tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">end in terms of improvement in Ofsted outcomes, they represent a far larger data set and the timescale for comparison is only three years.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is, however, clear from the data is that the impact of academisation on measurable outcomes is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other fact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ors, such a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prior attainment, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leadership and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the characteristics of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pupil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cohort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all have a substantially greater impact on school improvement and performance than the status of the school. The key difference for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aintained schools is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the quality of Local Authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support which schools in a category receive. Ofsted monitoring report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s now comment on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LA support and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overwhelming ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">jority of these reports for Hampshire schools, the comments endorse the quality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of that support, particularly in the rapid improvement of schools causing concern. Whilst sponsorship has been an effective tool for some schools, the impact in terms of Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is variable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> For converter academies, some of the decline in results is obscured by higher overall headline figures but Ofsted judgements reveal a gradual diminution of quality over time. Since leadership and pupil cohorts are largely unchanged, the quality of self-ev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aluation and support must raise some concerns.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We believe the quality and capacity of that support and responsiveness from some academy sponsor chains may be a different issue</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Learning from the Isle of Wight</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our perspective from Hampshire is now further e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nhanced by our unique additional responsibility for a separate local authority school system on the Isle of Wight.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted inspected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Isle of Wight’s performance of its school improvement function in the spring of 2013 following an inadequate judgement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Safeguarding at the end of 2012. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were judged to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inadequate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the school system on the isla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significantly underperforming.  GCSE results in 2012 were in the region of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a shocking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fifteen percentage points below the national aver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">age; Key Stage 2 results were poor  Exclusions from school in the secondary sector were high and school attendance in that sector by far the worst in the country.  The most recent figures from Ofsted show that the island has half the proportion of outstand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing schools as in England as a whole and five times the proportion of schools that are inadequate.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The recent annual report revealed the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Isle of Wight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to have the worst secondary inspection performance in the country.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It was against this background that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he DfE issued a direction to the Isle of Wight Council to enter into a strategic partnership with Hampshire County Council so that the latter’s Children’s Services department could take over the running of the services that, statutorily, are the responsibi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lity of the Director of Children’s Services under the 2004 Act – children’s social care and education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Isle of Wight Council had encouraged secondary s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chools to become academies and,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rather than seeking to lead schools forward towards educational excellence on behalf of the island’s community, the Authority used schools’ growing self management, indeed autonomy, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to relinquish the role of the education authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It reduced its capaci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty to such an extent that it was no longer possible to offer leadership, challenge, support and intervention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lthough the few staff left worked very hard to fill the void, there is little evidence of concerted action by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to tackle problems co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mmon to a number of schools, little evidence of the kind of school to school collaboration that leads to higher standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Some primary headteachers, in particular, were deflected from their work in overseeing teaching and learning because they had to spe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd their time procuring support services, only tangentiall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y related to their core purpose.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is within that context that we can see that at least two large secondary schools became sponsored academies and deteriorated substantially and catastrophically.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The process of rebuilding a system and performance is now underway but whatever else can be said about the island’s school performance, it is not an advert for sponsored academy status.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 4.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-4.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence from Hampshire is that schools flourish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and improve when they are robustly but professionally challenged by a body with the authority, both statutory and moral,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and professional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expertise to do so and provided with appropriate and tailored support to improve.  Sponsorship of failing schools prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ides a route which can be effective in shifting stubbornly inadequate schools but it is not a panacea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. When a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school fails through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inadequacies in leadership it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be shifted more rapidly by an efficient local authority which has the capacity to intervene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> quickly and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decisively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Local authorities have a responsibility to know their schools well and target intervention and support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appropriately. This intervention must include, but not solely consist of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brokerage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of sponsorship.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Successful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s are the best tool in a local area for improving other schools and local authorities which do not maintain a detailed knowledge of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and relationship with, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the best schools in their administrative area, regar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dless of status, have no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ability to broker </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The support cannot confidently and coherently broker itself. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A model which focusses only on schools which fail is not a system which can improve.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Excellent school leadership is the best determinant of success and this exists in all types of schools. Where leadership is not excellent, isolation from the “system,” and avoidance of robust challenge and high quality support makes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">even schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where atta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inment had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> previously</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> vulnerable to rapid decline.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Academy status is largely irrelevant in terms of the capacity of a school to do well if leadership is good. However, when freedom equates to evasion, academy status is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relevant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the school to sustain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high performance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Where local authorities have withdrawn from the responsibilities they discharge on behalf of their population, or carry those responsibilities out inadequately, the system declines rapidly whether schools have be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">come academies or not.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="border-top-color:#622423; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:4.5pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>